# The build context becomes the repository itself inside the builder stage, so
# everything listed here is one of three things: regenerated inside the image,
# unusable inside it, or secret.

# Regenerated by muxbuild in the builder. Also, on a Windows host, this holds
# mux.exe and app binaries that are not even the right operating system —
# copying it in would let a stale, wrong-platform tree shadow the real build.
/runtime/

# Accounts, every user's app database, and pepper.key. This is the volume. It
# must never be a layer.
/data/

# Reinstalled by muxbuild's `npm ci`. Matched at any depth because each app
# checkout under apps/ has its own. Excluding these is not just about context
# size: node_modules is the one genuinely platform-specific input here (esbuild
# and rollup ship native binaries), so a Windows or macOS tree copied into an
# Alpine builder breaks the Astro build with an error about the wrong ELF.
**/node_modules/

# Windows binaries. Nothing in the image can execute them.
*.exe

# Scratch left behind by test/api.sh.
/test/.work/
.work/

# History is not a build input, and it is the largest thing in the context.
# .gitmodules is deliberately NOT excluded: it is the only place the app
# repository URLs are written down, and the Dockerfile reads it to clone any
# submodule that arrived empty. **/.git also drops the gitlink files inside the
# submodule checkouts, which point into the .git we just removed anyway.
.git
**/.git
.gitignore
.github/

# Read by people, not by muxbuild. Excluding them keeps a documentation edit
# from invalidating the build cache. examples/ is NOT excluded — static-notes
# is a working app source somebody may have added to apps.json.
/docs/
/test/
/patches/
README.md

# Compose files are for the host. .env in particular can hold MUX_PEPPER, which
# has no business in an image layer.
docker-compose*.yml
.env
.env.*
